How to become more CONSISTENT: 

💙 Stop saying you’re a perfectionist- this justifies you continuing a behavior when you are in fact not a victim of perfectionism but in COMPLETE CONTROL of your behavior/consistency.
💙 Plan ahead- the best “hack” very few people actually do. Winging it from meal to meal does not work. Plan your meals, workouts, even schedule the day before and stick with it. You will be amazed at how your consistency improves just by doing this.
💙 Narrow your focus to 1-2 things. Walking everyday, protein + veggies at each meal, etc. Trying to change everything at once often leads to changing nothing.
💙 Get rid of unrealistic expectations and timelines (the #1 progress killer). There’s no way to control how long things take so stop wasting that energy. Focus on what you CAN control- your effort, your mindset ✔️ 

Consistency is the ONLY thing that will guarantee success!! Make it a habit, a routine, a lifestyle and it’s innate with you for life. 
YOU GOT THIS 👏🏼

TERYAKI GLAZED TOFU (gluten free!) 

Step 1: MARINATE - in a large bowl whisk together:
🔸 1/2 cup gf teriyaki sauce (I love @primalkitchenfoods GF teryaki sauce)
🔸 1/2 cup gf soy sauce (I love kikkoman GF soy sauce) 
🔸 2 garlic cloves minced 
🔸 1/2 teaspoon honey 
🔸 1 teaspoon mirin 
🔸 1 teaspoon sake 

Step 2: TOFU- cut into cubes and add into marinade carefully (it’s very delicate and can break easily so be careful!) 
*PRO TIP: take paper towels and dry tofu for as long as possible before cooking. The dryer the tofu = the crispier it comes out*

Step 3: 
🔸 Preheat oven to 425 degrees
🔸 Heat up toasted sesame oil in large sauté pan and cook each piece of tofu on medium-high heat 2-3 min on each side
🔸 Add tofu onto baking pan and use spoon to scoop the extra marinade leftover in the bowl onto each piece of tofu
🔸 Sprinkle sesame seeds and stick in oven for 15 minutes- then FLIP each piece of tofu and cook another 10 minutes to get that perfect crispy sear on each piece.

Enjoy 😍

Sunday Night Balls!

What you need:
🌱 1 yellow onion diced 
🌱 1 egg 
🌱 Chopped fresh parsley
🌱 Chopped fresh Basil 
🌱 Chopped fresh dill 
🌱 3 garlic cloves minced 
🌱 1/2 cup GF bread crumbs 
🌱 2 tablespoons ketchup
🌱 Salt + pepper
🌱 Ground chicken/turkey/beyond meat or red meat (whatever you prefer as long as it’s ground) 
🌱 1 jar tomato sauce

Directions:
1. Preheat oven to 400 degrees & prep large baking pan with foil or parchment paper 
2. In a large bowl mix together onion, egg, herbs, breadcrumbs, garlic, ketchup, salt, pepper and ground meat— combine well 
3. You can ball if cooking immediately or cover and let sit in the refrigerator until ready to cook- helps the mixture set
4. In a large pot, heat up tomato sauce on a low simmer (add basil into the sauce for extra flavor!)
5. Shape balls, place on baking sheet then into the oven for 15 minutes— from there they go straight into the saucepan to cook another 20 minutes

This recipe is one of my OG healthy alibi recipes! I’ve modified it slightly over the years but it is a STAPLE and a guaranteed family favorite. Hope you guys enjoy! Xx

6 quick tips to beat the mommy monday blues:

1️⃣ MAKE A TO-DO LIST. Sometimes the workload and balancing act is so overwhelming it’s hard to know where to begin to get things done and we end up getting nothing done at all. Making a short and realistic to-do list helps you take control. Crossing things off on the list is the best feeling!
2️⃣ GET OUT OF THE HOUSE. Fresh air and vitamin D can do a world of good. Put the kids in the stroller and go for a walk or take them to the park. Getting out is an immediate mood booster. Plus, playing in the park gets the kids tired and this means less bedtime drama 🤌🏼
3️⃣ NOURISHING BREAKFAST. Starting off Monday with a healthy meal sets the tone for a week of eating real, whole foods. You’d be surprised at how much this actually helps you to feel good and get ready to take on the challenges of the week.
4️⃣ MOVE YOUR BODY. Movement of any kind is absolutely therapeutic. Walking, running, an at home workout, in studio, dancing in the mirror- virtually ANY kind of movement will get your endorphins pumping and have a positive affect on your mental health. 
5️⃣ PRACTICE GRATITUDE. Take a few moments on a Monday morning to jot down or journal what you’re grateful for. By refocusing your mind on what’s good in your life instead of those little things that are frustrating, you’re inviting positive thoughts in and setting yourself up to be in a better mood, have a better day and a good week.
6️⃣ SHOW YOURSELF GRACE. With all of the pressure to be a perfect parent these days it can be so hard to actually relax. Moms are ridiculously hard on themselves, but it’s important to remember that we are HUMAN. We all “lose our shit” sometimes…and that’s okay and perfectly normal! It’s okay to not get a million things done successfully in one day. It’s okay to be late for an appointment once in a while, show yourself GRACE and know you are doing your best ❤️

The perfect salad does exist! 🤤 Key ingredient: CUTLETS 🙌🏼

Directions for cutlets:
▫️Preheat oven to 400 degrees 
▫️Bread the cutlets- I like to mix panko + regular together 
▫️Heat up avocado or olive oil in large skillet & prep a large oven pan for transfer 
▫️Cook chicken in the pan for 4-5 minutes on each side then transfer chicken directly to the baking pan 
▫️Place pan in the oven and bake for another 15 minutes

That’s it! The key is to get the nuggets seared on the skillet before baking to get that perfect crispy crunch. Xx

Pro tip: if you have enough prep time, stick the breaded cutlets into the fridge for as little as 1 and as much as 24 hours before cooking. This helps the breadcrumbs stay on throughout the cooking process and I find gives a more crunchy taste to the cutlets in the end!

One of the BIGGEST hacks for productivity, organization & wellness reminders is actually utilizing our phones📱 You know those little devices with us at all times that distract us from getting any real work done throughout the day!? 😵‍💫 I have a few tips and tricks for how best to actually UTILIZE your phone so that your productivity, organization & wellness are optimally improved in 2023 🙌🏼

1. Turn OFF notifications (other than calendar reminders and phone call/text alerts) 
2. Schedule and utilize “focus mode” when you don’t want to be bothered by notifications as well as “do not disturb”. During a workout, in a meeting, out to dinner, or even just at home when you don’t want to be distracted. 
3. Schedule night shift a few hours before you go to bed at night- the warmer display is easier on the eyes and can lessen digital eye strain 
4. Set time limits for your most used apps so you don’t waste time scrolling when you actually need to get work done
5. Import health data and set up medical ID for yourself (incredibly helpful to know) and also for emergency situations 
6. Utilize the Fitness plus app (every single iPhone comes with this) for accountability, motivation and workout inspiration 
7. Set reminders to drink water, check in with a loved one, eat a nourishing meal, meditate, take time for yourself- utilizing the reminder features can work wonders especially if you’re super busy throughout the day
8. Be intentional with your smart phone usage. You want to ensure that you are in control of the phone and not the other way around. Make sure your phone usage benefits you somehow and doesn’t hinder your productivity or mental health ❤️

Also taking a break from the phone altogether if you can is completely refreshing! Any other smart phone tips or tricks you would add?

Lemon Chicken Recipe:

Ingredients:
1 teaspoon oregano
1/4 cup olive oil
Salt & pepper
1/2 cup fresh lemon juice
1 garlic clove
1 teaspoon rosemary
1 lemon chopped in wedges
2-3lbs chicken breasts
1/2 cup thyme

Directions: 
1. Preheat oven to 400 degrees
2. In medium bowl combine olive oil, salt, pepper, rosemary, garlic, oregano & fresh lemon juice 
3. Place trimmed chicken breast cutlets in marinade (stick in fridge for an hour or 2 if there’s time for extra flavor!) 
4. In a medium skillet sauté chicken in marinade on medium-high heat for 3-4 minutes on each side then transfer to baking pan
5. Place fresh thyme and lemon wedges on top and bake chicken another 10-15 minutes 
6. Take out and enjoy!

Let’s talk BALANCE 🙏🏼 I get so many messages asking how I manage to balance it all as a mom with a career and still make time for myself, my husband, my family & my friends. On the outside everything may look easy and seamless but the truth is it’s really challenging. 

A few tips I live by:

1. Divide your time, not your attention. Whatever I am doing I give 100% of my focus to- whether that’s being with the kids, a client session, hanging with loved ones, recording a reel, working out, etc. 
2. Don’t sacrifice your sleep to get things done. Good sleep and proper rest are essential to balance all things successfully. Without it I personally have a really hard time functioning and getting anything done at all. 
3. Don’t blame yourself or feel shame/guilt if you can’t be at every pickup or take them to every activity. Multitasking is hard AF and if you are a working mom you know that sacrifice comes with the job description. Be kind to yourself, know that you are doing your best and all of your hard work does not go unnoticed- it matters. 
4. Just say no. Setting boundaries and protecting your energy are necessary mindset shifts in my book. Spending  time in positive environments with positive people who support and love your evolution and growth and saying no to negative energy that does not serve you.
5. Accept help & support when it’s needed. Be communicative with your partner, family & friends about what you need from them to thrive. Asking for help is a necessary part of motherhood - it’s not always easy to do but it makes a world of difference.
6. Always leave time for YOU. You matter, your mental health matters, your physical health matters. You can’t pour from an empty cup- taking care of yourself is ESSENTIAL to being fully present as a mother and in every other role you fill. Prioritize you 💗

5️⃣ FaceTime a friend when you would normally spend that time criticizing your body (interpersonal connection is extremely nourishing for the soul especially when entering into a negative mindset).
6️⃣ Be mindful of your hunger cues- recognize your body’s “full” signals and satiated feelings & emotions.
7️⃣ Be mindful of the language you are using to yourself and to others around food- negativity radiates inner and outer negativity and transversely positivity radiates inward and outer positivity. Change your language, change your mindset🙌🏼

Remember punishment, restriction, shame & guilt have NO home in a healthy & happy body + mind. Step into your power!!! You got this ❤️

GG’S HOMEMADE CHICKEN SOUP aka JEWISH PENICILLIN: 

What you need: 6 chicken breasts on the bone, 4 Turkey necks (best to use kosher chicken/turkey bc of salt content), dill, parsley, cilantro, 5 large carrots, 2 leeks, 1/2 celery root, 3 parsnips, 1/2 Savoy cabbage and salt. 

Steps 1-4 are for CLEANING purposes not cooking purposes. The goal is to have as CLEAR of a soup as possible so these steps are ESSENTIAL to outcome of the soup.

1. In large pot bring water to boil and let turkey cook for 3-4 min then pour out water and wash Turkey with cold water. 
2. Wipe out the pot, put chicken + turkey necks in & bring water to boil. Put chicken in for 3-5 min then wash with cold water. WASH POT.
3. Put turkey and chicken in pot with water and salt and bring to a soft boil.
4. Take a spoon and remove all foam, red spots or any other debris out of pot while boiling. Once water is clear, add all vegetables except for dill, cilantro, parsley and savoy cabbage.
5. After cleaning veggies add carrots, parsnip, celery root & leeks to pot. Let cook making sure that the soup looks very clear before adding the veggies.
6. Wait 20 minutes and add herbs & cover pot 3/4 of the way. Add water if necessary. Lower heat to low flame and let cook for 3 hours. Add salt and keep tasting every hour.
7. Taste & make sure soup has enough salt. In the last 30 minutes of cooking add in Savoy cabbage.
8. When soup is finished strain into containers- if you wish to use chicken & veggies that were cooked into the soup, strain them in separate containers and add in amounts preferred as you heat up soup.
9. White rice or any small pasta goes well as noodles to put in the soup. 

PRO TIP*: DO NOT CHOP ANY VEGETABLES. Other than celery root you peel and halve (GG clearly states the vegetables break apart and chopping is a waste of time)
PRO TIP 2: Only reheat portion of soup that you will eat at that moment because otherwise soup will get sour. Xx

Sunday Night Balls!

Ingredients:
🌱 1 yellow or white onion diced 
🌱 1 egg 
🌱 Chopped fresh parsley 
🌱 Chopped fresh dill 
🌱 2-3 garlic cloves minced 
🌱 1/2 cup GF bread crumbs 
🌱 2 tablespoons ketchup
🌱 Salt + pepper
🌱 Ground chicken/turkey/beyond meat or red meat (whatever you prefer as long as it’s ground!)

Directions:
1. Preheat oven to 400 degree & prep large baking pan with foil or parchment paper 
2. In a large bowl mix together onion, egg, herbs, breadcrumbs, garlic, ketchup, salt, pepper and ground meat— combine well 
3. You can ball if cooking immediately or cover and let sit in the refrigerator until ready to cook- helps the mixture set
4. Shape balls, place on greased up baking sheet then into oven for 15 minutes— flip over carefully and cook another 15 minutes. That’s it!

BRUSCHETTA 🌿🍅 mushroom + regular. A dinner party favorite!

Ingredients:
+ baby portobello mushrooms 
+ French baguette 
+ 1 tablespoon extra virgin olive oil
+ 6-7 plum tomatoes diced
+ 1/3 cup chopped fresh Basil
+ 1oz grated parmigiana cheese 
+ 2 garlic cloves minced
+ salt & pepper
+ 1 tablespoon high quality balsamic vinaigrette 

Directions:
+ preheat oven to 425 degrees
+ Wash mushrooms & take stems out of each one. Place on a baking pan plain face up (no oil needed as the mushrooms bake they bleed water). Stick in oven for about 15 minutes.
+ Slice baguette, brush olive oil onto one side and stick in oven to lightly toast (about 10 minutes)
+ Gather all bruschetta ingredients in large mixing bowl and combine well
+ once mushrooms & baguette is done, take out of oven and use a small spoon to scoop the bruschetta into each one. Best to eat ASAP!

Nothing makes me happier than taking the time to plan and write out my dinners for the week then go to the market and make it all happen. When I was pregnant with David I made the transition to a completely organic household and it truly changed the quality of the food I consumed, my general mood after meals, my energy levels & skin quality. I encourage all of you to do the same and here’s why.

Benefits of eating ORGANIC:
1️⃣Organically grown food has more vitamins, minerals, nutrients & enzymes compared to commercially grown food.
2️⃣Although it’s pricier, research shows that organic food can help you lose weight bc it’s free of obesogens which are a chemical compound found on pesticides that lead to weight gain.
3️⃣Organic food tastes better bc the soil is well balanced & nourished.
4️⃣Organic food can’t be genetically modified so it’s easy to avoid GMO foods.
5️⃣Purchasing organic means you will avoid hormones, antibiotics & other harmful drugs that can lead to cancer & diseases.
6️⃣It’s generally better for the environment when you make a conscious effort to eat organic.

Let’s talk about intuitive eating 💕 For those who are unfamiliar, intuitive eating is actually a recovery lifestyle for chronic dieters. It’s for those who need to make peace with food but also for those who want to feel connected to the food they’re eating. It focuses on nurturing the body rather than “restricting” which diet culture unfortunately encourages. It allows you to reach your natural weight that you were meant to be by STRENGTHENING your connection with food in a mindful & purposeful way. 

Until I was diagnosed with #celiacdisease over 7 years ago I had no idea what #intuitiveeating truly meant. After my diagnosis, I went through a down period and really struggled with what to eat as a newbie to celiac life. I ate mainly GF pasta, rice, bread, etc. overcompensating for not being able to eat gluten with eating GF versions of all my favorite carbs thinking it was “healthier” because it was gluten free. It really didn’t feel right in my body and I felt completely out of whack and extremely confused.

I then began researching & learning about celiac disease & in turn the practice of intuitive eating— improvising as a beginner chef in the kitchen. I began cooking real food from the earth that felt right in my body and made me feel GOOD from the inside out. I had no training or cooking background but the more I cooked the more confidence I gained in the kitchen. Within a few months my entire body composition & attitude changed. I ate to nourish myself, started my health coaching certification program and had a new goal in my life: to help others struggling with similar issues find their way to mentally & physically feeling good again 🩷 

So to anyone struggling on a similar journey right now please know that there is hope. You will find your way it just may take a little time. Show yourself grace, kindness & patience and above all else learn to trust the process. Difficult roads often lead to beautiful destinations 🤌🏼

I always set new intentions for myself come September because it’s a great way to refocus and get back on track post summer. 
Below are some tips on HOW I do this for those looking for a bit of guidance:

🩷 REFLECT. What values do you want to embody? What decisions will get you closer to where you want to be? How do you want to feel?
🩷 WRITE THEM DOWN. Writing down your intentions will help make them more tangible and puts them out into the universe to help them come to life.
🩷 KEEP THEM POSITIVE. Instead of setting an intention like “stress less” flip it into “be calm, relax & trust that everything will work out as it should” Focus on the positive.
🩷 MAKE THEM VISIBLE. Hang them up in a spot that you spend a lot of your time. Revisit them frequently so you’re constantly reminded of what you’re working on.
🩷 GIVE YOURSELF FEEDBACK. Do an “evening check” or use visual reminders throughout the day to reflect on what you’re doing great on and what could use a little extra work. 
🩷 HAVE FUN! Remember that this is a fun, guiding practice to help you take small steps to improving yourself each day- it’s not about perfection.

2. Wash thoroughly with water, separating each leaf to make sure it’s clean
3. Prep a medium pot of boiling water and add in a few garlic cloves, bay leaves & a lemon slice- then add in artichokes.
4. Once it’s boiling change to a medium simmer and cover for 1.5 hours
5. That’s it!

Artichokes might appear intimidating but they’re low cal, high in fiber, antioxidants, vitamins + minerals. Stress eating & how to combat it.

Food is comfort and when we feel stressed we often use food as a numbing/distraction strategy to create a buffer between ourselves and whatever difficult feelings we might be experiencing. 

So how do we help this? 

The first step is to recognize the difference between emotional hunger vs physical hunger. Some signs of emotional eating to look out for:
	1.	Sudden or urgent cravings
	2.	Craving only certain foods
	3.	Overeating or binge eating
	4.	Feels of shame or guilt right after 

If you know you tend to be an emotional eater and you recognize 1 or more of these signs the next step is to figure out the root cause of the underlying emotions behind the stress and find different coping strategies to deal with what you are going through. 

When you recognize the emotional moment of hunger coming on try to redirect your body & mind to do something that will bring a more positive aftermath. Some examples:
	1.	Go for a walk
	2.	Have a cup of tea
	3.	Take a bath
	4.	Move your body
	5.	Mealprep/cooking therapy
	6.	Call a family member or good friend 

Most importantly be kind to yourself and live inside of a judge-free zone. Use self compassion and remember you are human. The world is tense & heavy right now and not everything is going to go according to our health plans. That’s okay 🩷

Ingredients:
1 bag split peas
Chopped onion, celery & carrots 
Olive oil
3 minced garlic cloves 
3-4 bay leaves 
1 box vegetable or chicken stock
Salt & pepper

Reset, Recharge & Recover 🙌🏼

The most important 3 R’s of training that took me years to understand. Exercise, like most things in life, is all about balance and time out is an ESSENTIAL part of any workout regimen. The biggest mistake people make when beginning their fitness journey is training frequently and not taking enough time to rest. If you don’t factor rest into your regimen, your performance will suffer and you will burn out quicker. Rest days allow your body - and your mind - time to recover from workouts and also gives your body time to ADAPT to your training to grow stronger & fitter so you’ll be in a better mental & physical place to make the next workout count + push yourself to reach your goals 👊🏼

All you need:

~ 3-4 Yellow onion (again depends how many potatoes you have!)
~ 2-4 eggs

Directions:
1. Start by grating the potatoes and using a paper towel or a cheese cloth to get as much water out of them as possible (the more water you can take out the crispier the latkes will be!)
2. Chop up onion (I used a veggie chopper) and add into the grated potatoes 
3. Add in 2 eggs and see if it’s sticky enough- if not add more
4. Bring pan to medium-high heat and using an ice cream scooper or small measuring cup form latkes (better to do smaller because they’ll be thinner & more crispy!) 
5. Flip once the edges are browned and don’t forget to salt as you go! 

This is my family recipe we have always used for our Chanukah latkes! No flour, no matzoh meal just potato, onion & egg. It’s completely #glutenfree and absolutely DELICIOUS. Even if you don’t celebrate Chanukah you will still enjoy these latkes (they also make great mealprep!).

Hearty Minestrone Soup 🥣 

Ingredients:
~ chopped celery, onion, carrots & green beans 
~ 2-3 minced garlic cloves 
~ 1 large can diced tomatoes
~ 1 can cannelloni beans 
~ Veggie stock
~ Bay leaves 
~ Fresh thyme
~ Fresh oregano 
~ salt & pepper to taste 

Directions:
1. Start by sautéing onion, carrots, green beans & celery with just olive oil, salt & pepper in a large pot 
2. Add in garlic cloves, diced tomatoes & cannelloni beans & mix well 
3. Add in vegetable stock, bay leaves, oregano & thyme. Cover pot and let simmer for 60-70 minutes
4. That’s it! 

No blending or complications necessary this soup is so delicious, nutritious and easy to make. The whole family will love it and you’ll make it all season long. Enjoy! xx 🥣
